If you use the printable representation of the hash, the dictionary of characters that the hash uses is only digits 0-9 and a-f. While they likely still won&#x27;t guess this, it&#x27;s better to use 40 characters of the printable output of /dev/urandom directly, e.g.:<p><pre><code>  dd if=/dev/urandom bs=512 count=1 | strings -n1 | tr -d &#x27;
&#x27;
</code></pre>
Edit: the original question, before it was deleted, was whether using a hash of data from /dev/urandom would result in a good password.
